stylometry:
The data mining method I remember from class was about warehouses. We had data about customers - their x&y coordinates, their annual demand, and how far away from the warehouses. We were trying to use their information to find location and how far away they were from the warehouses.
Other examples that use data - were the data clusters we solved, both with cities and my personal one with cereals. The object was to find a data set that can be clustered - clearly, to find trends (exactly what data mining is used for). In cereal clusters - the data I obtained were nutrition facts about all different brands of one similar product -- cereal. I used 20 different cereals and all the same facts, including things like, calories, sugar, fats, serving size, etc. (IN city clusters - we had different ethnicities and every city, which had to include numbers of size, etc). In our problems we had our basic information (from the data) then our standardized, and inputs. You had to create the changing cells, introduce Vlookup, etc. and rows to offset the calculations. When running solver - you must use evolutionary solver to find the "good" solution. In both cases, running it a couple times gave us our best fit decision and categorized the data like we intended it would.
